<gtr:personRoles><gtr:personRole url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/34209B7C-5A1B-4A0B-86C2-42456A345D52"><gtr:id>34209B7C-5A1B-4A0B-86C2-42456A345D52</gtr:id><gtr:firstName>Steven</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Van de Walle</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF003188%2F1"><gtr:id>F46A6C78-1006-4163-8483-AB68BA6EB686</gtr:id><gtr:title>Public attitudes towards services of general interest in comparative perspective</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F003188/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Public services do not function as just any other private service. Rather than just delivering something, public services also have an important role in the social and regional identity of a country. Closing a remote train line or subsidising a post office in a small village has important implications that go beyond the mere presence or disappearance of the service. European debates on of Services of General Interest reflect different perspectives on the trade-off between efficiency or economy and equity and universality in the reform of public service delivery.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p>

&lt;p>When citizens express their attitudes towards such public services as mail delivery, public transport, or electricity supply, these attitudes are not just a reflection of the experienced service quality. These attitudes are also a reflection of the social, political and ideological values citizens cherish in the delivery and organisation of public services.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>In this project, Steven Van de Walle will analyse determinants of public attitudes towards services of general interest in a European comparative perspective. This analysis will contribute to our knowledge about public service values and administrative cultures in different European countries. For the analysis, existing Eurobarometer opinion surveys will be used.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-05-15</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-10-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>22906</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/F003188/1</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-153-27-0004</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5D762B83-597E-4E91-B2F7-04CBB955175C</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Pol. sci. &amp; internat. studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject></gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchTopics><gtr:researchTopic><gtr:id>F7EEE6CD-E283-4BAB-BA5E-70B4B0F1F1A6</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Political Science</gtr:text></gtr:researchTopic></gtr:researchTopics><gtr:rcukProgrammes/></gtr:project></gtr:projectComposition></gtr:projectOverview>